About me

Goals and non-goals

  • Goal: To equip the audience with a seed of knowledge for when their current build system stops scaling.

  • Non-goal: To make the audience replace their existing build systems because of their shortcomings presented here.

    • Let me stress this point: Make and CMake are fine tools (when used appropriately) until they stop scaling.

Make, Problems and Mitigations

  • rule-based

  • comes with implicit rules

  • too easy to forget to declare some dependencies (a.k.a prerequisites)

  • environment variables leak to all action (a.k.a recipe) executions

  • Make does not rebuild on environment changes (e.g. CXX=other-compiler make)

  • changes to the Makefile are not picked up by Make

  • timestamps are the only attribute that determines a rebuild

    • can be mitigated by using ccache which is still executed but faster than expensive compiler calls

CMake, Problems and Mitigations

  • a buildsystem generator, sometimes also called a meta-buildsystem

  • (CMake is used here as one example for the group of buildsystem generators; see also: Meson, …)

  • commonly generates “UNIX Makefiles” and “Ninja” on Linux-based operating systems

  • fundamentally has the same problems as Make

https://abseil.io/resources/swe-book/html/ch18.html#task-based_build_systems

{ Fast, Correct } — Choose two

  • functional: action :: [input] -> [output]

  • types of inputs: files, environment variables, command line arguments, tools, …

  • phased: loading, analysis, execution phases (but: Project Skymeld)

  • sandboxed

  • language-agnostic

  • extensible

  • remote caching (ccache on steroids)

  • remote execution (distcc on steroids)

                                         It's about time for a demo

Live Demo: Summary

  • Starlark

    • A subset of Python.

    • Declarative in BUILD files, imperative in *.bzl files.

  • Powerful set of subcommands.

    • build, run, test, query, cquery, aquery, coverage, …

  • Bazel creates sandboxes for each action execution.

    • Different sandbox implementations with varying degree of isolation.

  • Tool command lines are relative to the sandbox root.

  • The auto-generated C++ toolchain is not hermetic.

  • Bazel provides additional architecture tools

    • Visibility

    • Layering Check (requires compiler support)

    • SCons calling Ant for one Eclipse plugin that used to be developed outside of the repo <1 minute

    • GNU Make calling Ant to build plugins for Eclipse (almost exclusively Java) 10 minutes

Case Study: Opportunities and Goals

  • This “zoo of build systems” offers a lot of low-hanging fruits.

  • Perfect scheduling across all cores on a host.

    • Requires a single dependency graph, i.e. all phases are to be merged into one.

  • Enabling remote caching as the most primitive form of distributed builds.

  • (Future) Enabling of remote execution to scale the builds on demand.

Case Study: Obstacles

  • The existing (test-)infrastructure assumes a polluted working copy (in-source build as opposed to out-of-source).

  • Age of the project.

  • Lost repository history (migration from ClearCase to Git).

  • Poorly written commit messages.

  • Developers have historically considered the build systems a black box.

  • Developers were used to a “focused build” - a build that did not update dependencies.

  • A management that is focussed on “customer value” and puts no emphasize at all on developer productivity.

  • (Almost) No prior knowledge in Bazel.

Migration: Don’t do it if any of the following is true:

  • You cannot praise your management like these guys do.

    • BazelCon 2019 Day 1: Building Self Driving Cars with Bazel

    • Building Self Driving Cars with Bazel - Part 2: Scaling

  • Your feature-developing software engineers have historically been treating the build system as a black box.

    • Ask yourself: Is my average coworker a software craftsman with a carefully curated toolbox?

  • You cannot assemble a platform team of highly-skilled (and highly-driven!) engineers.

The Bazel Ecosystem

  • Bazel

  • buildifier – formatter

  • buildozer – build file transformations

  • Gazelle – a build file generator

  • BCR – the Bazel Central Registry

    • Rules (extensions) for Bazel

    • third-party dependencies such as SQLite, Boost, Abseil, Catch2, Googletest, …

  • Remote Cache

  • Remote Execution Services

  • YouTube: bazelcon

Conclusion

  • clean is an anti-pattern

  • build files become increasingly abstract; there are at least two ways to deal with this

    • crank up the verbosity of the build system

    • understand the less powerful solutions first, then go on to the next

  • make, cmake, meson and the likes are sufficient when massive scale is not (yet) a requirement

    • … because if used as intended, they provide the same functional guarantees that Bazel provides

  • use Bazel when the former perform poorly on large projects

    • … and ccache is not sufficient, either

  • that being said, the features provided by Bazel are a welcome addition

    • visibility at the build system level

    • introspection into the build system using queries

    • derivatives of the build with Aspects
